the supreme court today agreed to hear the 
appeals of a california death row inmate who says the states 
capital punishment law does not give jurors enough discretion in 
sentencing 
the justices said they will review the case of richard boyde 
he challenged among other things that portion of the 
california death penalty law that requires sentencing juries to 
impose death if they find that aggravating factors outweigh 
mitigating ones 
boyde was condemned for the jan 15 1981 murder of dick 
gibson a riverside convenience store clerk police said boyde and 
carl ellison abducted gibson after robbing the store took him to a 
nearby orange grove and shot him 
ellison also was convicted and sentenced to 25 years to life 
boyde had been convicted of robbing the same convenience store 
five years earlier the stores clerk had been abducted that time 
also but was not killed 
the case is boyde vs california 886613 
