<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to consider 
reinstating the conviction and 35year prison sentence of a 
maryland man accused of armed robbery 
the justices said they will review a ruling that the conviction 
was tainted by evidence obtained unlawfully by police 
prince georges county police investigating the feb 3 1986 
armed robbery of a restaurant obtained arrest warrants for two 
suspects jerome buie and lloyd allen 
a half dozen police officers went to buies home in riverdale 
two days after the robbery and arrested him after entering the 
home they looked for him on the first and second floors 
one officer went to the basement stairs yelling for anyone who 
might be down there to come out 
buie eventually emerged and climbed the basement stairs to be 
searched handcuffed and arrested by the officer 
at that point another officer descended the stairs to the 
basement where he saw in plain view and then seized a red running 
suit a victim of the robbery had said that one of the robbers wore 
a red running suit 
prosecutors over buies objection used the running suit as 
evidence at his trial he was convicted and sentenced to 35 years 
in prison 
an intermediate state appeals court upheld the conviction but 
the maryland court of appeals the states highest court ruled by 
a 43 vote last nov 28 that buie is entitled to a new trial 
the state court said police wrongly searched the basement 
because they had neither a search warrant nor probable cause to 
believe they would find allen or any other accomplice in the 
basement 
while acknowledging that buie was arrested lawfully the state 
court said the running suit should have been excluded as evidence 
because it was seized in an unlawful police search 
the state court said police violated the ban on unreasonable 
searches and seizures imposed by the constitutions fourth 
amendment 
police who make arrests generally are allowed to conduct 
socalled sweep searches of the arrest area if they reasonably 
believe their safety is jeopardized 
but the state court said the facts in this case simply do not 
provide probable cause to support a reasonable belief that any 
other serious and demonstrable potentiality for danger existed 
in the appeal acted on today maryland prosecutors said other 
courts have not required police officers to have full probable 
cause to believe other persons are on the premises before 
conducting such searches 
they urged the justices to use buies case to fashion a 
standard for police officers and courts in such circumstances 
the prosecutors argued that the prince georges county police 
officers had a right and a duty to make certain that third 
persons including buies codefendant lloyd allen were not in 
buies basement 
the case is maryland vs buie 881369 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

