<TEXT>
medicare patients who want to use their own 
money to pay for an assistant surgeon in eye cataract operations 
lost a supreme court appeal today 
the court without comment left intact a federal law that 
generally prohibits paying assistants for such surgery 
medicare a federal health insurance program for people over 65 
paid surgeons 822 million and assistant surgeons 42 million for 
cataract operations in 1983 
the surgery involves removal of a clouded lens from the eye it 
is the most common form of eye operation for the elderly as some 
one million cataract removals are performed each year 
congress in 1986 passed a costcutting law that generally bars 
medicare reimbursement for assistant surgeons in cataract removals 
the law went beyond saving the government money for paying 
assistants in such cases it also barred medicare patients from 
using their own funds unless the services were approved by an 
insurance carrier or a state committee that reviews such medical 
costs 
a group of medicare patients in new york and california and eye 
doctors and their professional associations in the two states sued 
in federal court here challenging the law 
the us circuit court of appeals last august threw out the suit 
the appeals court rejected arguments that barring patients from 
using their own money to pay assistant surgeons violates 
constitutional privacy and liberty protections 
the appeals court said not all choices made by patients and 
their physicians are matters of privacy entitled to strict 
protection by the constitution 
in the case of choosing the number of surgeons participating 
in a surgical procedure designed to save sight the prerequisite 
to a successful privacy claim would be a definite showing of 
medical necessity and the unavailability of equally effective 
alternative therapy the appeals court said 
it said there is insufficient evidence that having an assistant 
present for cataract surgery is indispensable to patient 
wellbeing 
the appeals court also said it is premature for the courts to 
determine whether the patients were deprived of liberty without due 
process 
that claim first must be tested by having patients request 
permission from an insurance company or state review committee to 
pay an assistant the appeals court said only when such requests 
are denied might there be grounds for the courts to intervene 
in the appeal acted on today the patients said the law puts 
them in an unfair position they said they can either choose to 
have the operation without an assistant present or they must give 
up all medicare benefits and pay for the entire cost of medical 
treatment themselves 
the case is new york opthalmological society vs sullivan 
881146 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

