the supreme court today refused to postpone a 
pennsylvania death row inmates execution but in a strange twist 
of events a lower federal court already had granted a postponement 
the justices by a 54 vote denied an emergency request filed 
on behalf of roderick frey whose june 13 execution was to make him 
the first to die in pennsylvanias electric chair since 1962 
but a federal judge acting on a separate emergency request 
granted an indefinite stay of execution last week 
the supreme court request had been filed before the federal 
judge acted 
frey 52 was convicted of arranging the nov 8 1979 killing of 
his wife barbara jean she was fatally shot while driving to work 
in lancaster county 
frey confessed to hiring charles zehring for the murder the 
couples divorce was pending at the time 
the nations highest court already has agreed to review the 
constitutionality of pennsylvanias death penalty law a decision 
is expected during the court term that will begin next october 
a stillpending formal appeal filed on freys behalf raises the 
issue the court already is studying whether the state law 
improperly limits the discretion of juries in choosing life or 
death for convicted killers 
under pennsylvanias law a jury must impose the death penalty 
if it unanimously finds at least one aggravating circumstance 
and no mitigating circumstance 
the justices are being urged to rule that the state law results 
in impermissible mandatory death sentences 
the pennsylvania supreme court rejected that argument last 
october when it upheld the death penalty law 
state officials contend the state law is constitutional because 
despite its mandatory language nothing prevents a defendant from 
presenting any and all mitigating evidence to offset any 
aggravating circumstance 
dissenting from todays onesentence order denying freys 
emergency request were justices william j brennan thurgood 
marshall harry a blackmun and john paul stevens 
the case is frey vs pennsylvania a914 
