an unusual nonbinding trial is intended to 
help settle a 300 million lawsuit brought by the neighbors of a 
government uraniumprocessing plant in a case that might otherwise 
take weeks in court 
us district judge s arthur spiegel is presiding over the 
summary trial to encourage an agreement in the classaction 
suit representing about 14000 people who live within five miles of 
the feed materials production center in fernald ohio 
eight jurors were selected for the trial this morning and the 
court was briefly recessed before opening arguments were to begin 
the trial was expected to last about a week with final arguments 
set to begin next monday 
the residents charge that the plant owned by the energy 
department and operated from 1951 to 1985 by national lead of ohio 
inc contaminated the air water and soil with uranium radium and 
thorium as well as dangerous nonradioactive substances including 
asbestos chlorids and barium 
the plant processed uranium for use in the governments nuclear 
weapons national lead and its parent firm national lead 
industries are named in the suit residents claim the plant 18 
miles northwest of cincinnati caused them emotional stress and 
lowered property values 
the energy department denies the allegations but has begun a 
cleanup program and admitted that more than 300000 pounds of 
radioactive uranium oxide dust escaped into the atmosphere through 
faulty airfiltering systems 
cincinnati lawyer stanley m chesley representing the 
plaintiffs said he considers the summary trial a useful tool for 
encouraging a settlement which chesley said the energy department 
had been unwilling to negotiate 
