an evenly divided supreme court today upheld a 
texas death row inmates murder conviction and death sentence but 
left unresolved a key question on racial bias in criminal trials 
by a 44 vote the justices automatically upheld the conviction 
and sentence of philip tompkins who in 1981 killed mary d berry 
in houston 
the split vote was accompanied only by a twosentence unsigned 
opinion that upheld texas court rulings and said justice sandra day 
oconnor did not participate in the case 
it is not known how the other eight justices are split but the 
court is likely to search out another case offering the same 
question how difficult should it be for prosecutors to prove they 
did not exclude potential jurors because of their race 
if the high courts eight other votes remain constant in some 
future case oconnors vote will control the outcome 
lower federal courts and state courts have been confused in 
trying to implement a 1986 supreme court decision in which the 
justices banned prosecutors from taking race into account when 
picking jurors 
the 1986 ruling curtailed dramatically the traditionally broad 
power of prosecutors to strike prospective jurors from trials by 
using peremptory or automatic challenges 
the justices said the exclusion of potential jurors from any 
criminal trial because of their race violates the equalprotection 
rights of defendants and of those people excluded 
in the case acted on today a texas trial judge ruled that 
tompkins had made a preliminary showing of discrimination in the 
prosecutions use of peremptory challenges 
during jury selection the prosecutor struck all 13 potential 
black jurors as a result the jury that convicted tompkins who is 
black was composed totally of whites 
but the trial judge ruled that the prosecutor in tompkins case 
successfully explained her peremptory challenges as neutral 
relative clear and legitimate and not racially motivated 
a state appeals court upheld tompkins conviction and death 
sentence but noted that arguments by his lawyers cast 
considerable doubt upon the neutral explanations offered by counsel 
for the state 
lower courts have disagreed over just how stringently they 
should evaluate a prosecutors explanation of allegedly racially 
motivated exclusions of potential jurors 
the case is tompkins vs texas 876405 
