<TEXT>
the supreme court in a victory for artists 
and authors said today a homelessrights group does not own 
exclusively the copyright to a sculpture it commissioned an artist 
to create 
the 90 decision ordered further lower court hearings to 
determine whether the community for creative nonviolence ccnv 
and its founder mitch snyder may share in the copyright of a work 
entitled third world america that depicts the plight of the 
homeless 
justice thurgood marshall writing for the court said the 
sculpture is a work made for hire and therefore its creator 
james earl reid of baltimore must at least share in the copyright 
marshall said ccnv did not become the copyright owner just 
because it played an active role in designing the work and may 
control its display reid is a freelance artist not an employee 
of ccnv he said 
transforming a commissioned work into a work by an employee on 
the basis of the hiring partys right to control the work is 
inconsistent with the workforhire provisions of a 1976 
federal copyright law marshall said 
ccnv based in the nations capital decided in 1985 to 
participate in the annual christmas pageant of peace here by having 
reid help create a display dramatizing the plight of the homeless 
reid using a synthetic substance tinted to resemble bronze 
scuplted two adult figures and a child huddled on a streetside 
steam grate 
the lifesized figures were intended as part of an updated 
nativity scene 
ccnv provided a steam grate and pedestal for the work 
reid was paid 15000 for expenses and for his assistants he 
donated his own services without charge 
ccnv sent the entire sculpture back to reid in january 1986 for 
some repairs 
the group planned to take the sculpture on a tour of several 
cities to raise money for the homeless 
but reid objected to the tour because he said the sculpture 
was too fragile he urged ccnv to cast the work in bronze or make a 
master mold that would withstand the tour 
ccnv declined but said reid could do so if he wished 
two months later reid refused to return the sculpture and 
registered it in his own name he also said he planned to take the 
work on a less ambitious exhibition tour 
ccnv then filed a lawsuit claiming exclusive copyright ownership 
of the sculpture 
a federal judged ruled in favor of the organization but the 
us court of appeals here overturned the judges decision 
ordering further hearings in the dispute to determine whether ccnv 
is entitled to share in the copyright 
a group representing more than 100000 artists and authors urged 
the supreme court to uphold the appeals court decision 
the reputation and income of freelance artists depends on their 
ability to own the copyrights of their works the group said 
the case is community for creative nonviolence vs reid 88293 
</TEXT>
