<TEXT>
south african and un officials said 
today they reached a tentative agreement to scrap discriminatory 
laws in namibia and clear the way for more than 40000 namibian 
refugees to begin returning home 
officials said pretoria agreed to abolish remaining 
discriminatory laws in namibia end detentions without trial and 
provide amnesty for black nationalist guerrillas who have fought 
for 23 years to oust south africa from this mineralrich territory 
louis pienaar south africanappointed administrator of namibia 
and un envoy martti ahtisaari reached the agreement on the 
discriminatory laws last week according to their spokesmen 
south african president pw botha was to sign legislation 
enacting the accords today or tuesday the spokesmen said 
with the signing by president botha the un high 
commissioner for refugees will be told immediately to start the 
repatriation of refugees said un spokesman fred eckhardt 
un officials have registered 41000 namibian refugees in 
angola and zambia who could start returning home early next week 
officials said 
south africa which has ruled the territory for 74 years agreed 
to a un independence plan that began april 1 and will lead to 
november elections 
returning refugees will include members of the southwest africa 
peoples organization which is widely favored to win the 
elections it is unclear however if the organization will be able 
to capture the twothirds majority necessary to control a new 
government 
campaigning is to begin july 1 but none of the movements 
senior exiled leaders has returned 
several matters remain unresolved including voter registration 
procedures and the release of political prisoners pienaar and 
ahtisaari met today and will meet again to discuss these questions 
their spokesmen said 
namibian authorities say they hold 29 political prisoners while 
the guerrilla organization says authorities recently released 201 
dissidents 
more than 4000 un personnel are in namibia to monitor the 
transition to independence 
under the plan south africa has withdrawn 46000 of its troops 
leaving less than 4000 in namibia that number should be reduced 
