<TEXT>
michigan hopes to save millions of dollars 
with a new program designed to keep aids victims off the medicaid 
rolls by paying their private insurance premiums 
the twoyear pilot program given final legislative approval 
last week is already being discussed by other states and likely 
will be copied if it proves successful said state rep david 
hollister 
the program is aimed at someone who has a job has insurance 
and at some point they lose their job because of their illness 
said hollister who got the idea for the program while attending a 
workshop of the national academy of science on insurance companies 
and aids 
they can continue their insurance for up to 18 months at their 
own expense after they lose their job but most people dont have 
18 months of reserves to pay that he said so at a certain 
point theyre going to lose their insurance and at that point they 
become impoverished and we pay it out of medicaid 
the cost of treating a person with acquired immune deficiency 
syndrome in michigan is about 1600 a month the state share of 
medicaid expenditures usually is about 45 percent or 724 
insurance premiums vary with different policies the average 
cost of a health plan offered to state employees is about 135 a 
month 
if an aids patient becomes too sick to work and continue paying 
insurance premiums medicaid could save about 1465 a month per 
person by paying the private insurance premium 
the state predicts about 180 people will participate in the 
program this year saving the state about 323000 370 in 1990 
saving 26 million and 580 in 1992 saving 41 million 
it is scheduled to start oct 1 as a threecounty experiment in 
the metropolitan detroit counties of wayne oakland and macomb 
which are home to about 70 percent of the states aidsinfected 
population 
the trickiest part is to make sure the state only pays the 
premiums for the people who would have become medicaid eligible 
said scott merwin a senior analyst with the department of social 
services medicaid division who wrote the proposal with hollister 
most people would become eligible for the program after they 
have lost their jobs and their disability insurance has expired 
critics say that the plan takes into account only participants 
incomes not assets and that the largest growing population of 
aids carriers intravenous drug users likely never had insurance 
at all 
robert lundy legislative officer for the michigan organization 
for human rights a homosexuallesbian group based in detroit said 
he was pleased with the program but didnt think it went far 
enough noting it only covered three counties 
the insurance industry which has the most to lose with the 
setup has responded mildly 
an inforce insurance policy is an inforce insurance policy 
if an aids patient borrows the money from uncle harry that policy 
is good said robert waldron director of the new york office of 
the health insurance association of america the trade association 
represents about 85 percent of the commercial health insurers in 
the country 
theyre obliged to pay thats the business theyre in in 
fact our advice has been hang on to that insurance policy beg 
borrow try not to steal but hang on to that insurance policy 
why should we complain waldron asked 
even blue cross and blue shield of michigan which has to take 
all comers regardless of illness backs the idea 
this seems to be a fairly restricted approach and its aimed 
at just those aids patients who have insurance already said 
dennis larson public relations coordinator for the company it 
doesnt lead me down the road to believe the states going to be 
recruiting aids patients to get on insurance 
as of may 8 1120 cases of aids had been reported in michigan 
since 1981 and 650 of those patients had died the centers for 
disease control in atlanta reported that as of april 30 there were 
90280 cases nationwide and 54402 of those people died 
aids weakens the bodys immune system and leaves it susceptible 
to cancers and infections it is transferred through the exchange 
of body fluids most often through sexual intercourse and sharing 
contaminated hypodermic needle or syringes 
