<TEXT>
the political fallout from the death of 
irans ayatollah ruhollah khomeini is likely to prolong the 
captivity of western hostages held by proiranian shiite moslem 
extremists in lebanon 
most of the 15 captives including nine americans are held by 
factions believed controlled by hezbollah or party of god irans 
main lebanese ally 
hezbollahs spiritual guide sheik mohammed hussein fadlallah 
has tried in vain to keep his party out of the power struggle 
between rival factions in tehran for supremacy in the postkhomeini 
era 
hezbollah militants backed by some 3000 iranian revolutionary 
guards based in the ancient roman city of baalbek in eastern 
lebanon have sided with irans hardliners led by interior minister 
ali akbar mohtashemi according to shiite sources who spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
yet the partys political leadership in beiruts southern slums 
hezbollahs main power base is aligned with tehrans socalled 
pragmatists led by parliament speaker hashemi rafsanjani the 
sources said 
rafsanjani holds hezbollahs purse strings 
no one can tell how badly this split will reflect on the 
hostages but its going to be bad said one source close to 
fadlallah 
