<TEXT>
the supreme court today set the stage for an 
important antitrust ruling agreeing to decide whether a major oil 
companys pricecutting plan illegally harmed independent dealers 
the justices said they will review a ruling that revived a 
lawsuit for triple damages against atlantic richfield co arco by 
independent gas stations in california and washington state 
the high court will hear arguments in the case in its next term 
beginning in october with a ruling likely in 1990 
usa petroleum co an independent oil dealer accused arco of 
conspiring with arco gas station dealers to fix prices illegally to 
drive the smaller independents out of business 
arco said its plan lowering gasoline prices to attract more 
customers and discontinuing credit cards to save money is 
legitimate 
arco said its share of the retail gasoline market in california 
and washington was 10 percent to 12 percent in 1981 and increased 
to 14 percent to 16 percent in 1983 as a result of the lower prices 
a federal judge threw out the suit against arco but the 9th 
us circuit court of appeals in a 21 ruling reinstated it last 
october 
the appeals court said that even though there is no proof that 
arco engaged in predatory pricing it still may have injured usa in 
violation of federal antitrust law 
the objective and effect of arcos illegal pricing scheme has 
been to reduce the number of independent gasoline retailers the 
appeals court said this is the type of injury that the antitrust 
rules were meant to prevent 
predatory pricing is defined as setting prices below the level 
necessary to sell a product or below an appropriate measure of the 
cost of producing the product 
in urging the supreme court to hear its appeal arco said the 
7th us circuit court of appeals based in chicago has handed down 
rulings in direct conflict with the 9th circuit court decision 
the case is atlantic richfield vs usa petroleum 881668 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

