<TEXT>
three out of five newspaper people rate their 
paper as adequate but not outstanding and even most of their 
bosses feel that way according to a survey released monday by the 
american society of newspaper editors 
four editors who presented the study at a news conference said 
that given the selfcritical nature of the business they were not 
surprised that only 34 percent of reporters copy editors 
photographers and news executives rated their papers very high 
five percent put the paper down as poor while 61 percent chose 
to describe them as adequate 
when only executives were counted the ratings were somewhat 
higher fortysix percent gave their papers a very high rating 
54 percent thought they were only adequate and 1 percent ranked 
them as poor 
only on big papers those with circulations over 250000 did a 
bare majority 52 percent rate their papers highly 
asne president loren ghiglione editor of the southbridge 
mass news and past president john seigenthaler editor and 
publisher of the nashville tennessean said so selfcritical an 
attitude was healthy and reflected the idealism of journalists 
seigenthaler recalled that in his career as a reporter he had a 
low regard for his paper on days his stories were cut or not 
prominently displayed 
linda grist cunningham executive editor of the parsippany 
nj daily record said the ratings may demonstrate disagreement 
between editors and reporters over a papers mission if the paper 
sees its job as covering the city council thoroughly but the 
reporter sees it as investigative journalism those results would 
be inevitable and would show the paper needs to communicate 
better with staff and readers alike what were supposed to be 
doing she said 
and barbara a henry editor of the rochester ny timesunion 
and democrat and chronicle said the results reflect a tendency 
among journalists to be more critical than other people of their 
performance 
when we get together we talk about what isnt good she said 
the findings were drawn from 1200 valid responses out of 1345 
sought from 72 newspapers chosen randomly in circulation groups 
to represent a crosssection of the nations nearly 55000 
professionals on nearly 1600 daily papers 
fiftyfour percent of participants said the paper was getting 
better that view was especially prevalent among people on big 
papers and people who had been with their paper 25 years or more 
thirteen percent said the paper was getting worse 33 percent saw 
it as marking time 
a third of participants thought newspapers will be less 
important in american life by the year 2000 than now twelve 
percent said they will be more vital and 55 percent saw no change 
only 42 percent of participants gave their immediate superior a 
high rating 45 percent rated the boss as adequate and 13 percent 
as poor 
other findings 
copy editors who edit reporters stories before they are 
published give their jobs a lower rating than other people in the 
newsroom when asked to compare it to previous work fortythree 
percent thought newspapers will be less important than now in the 
year 2000 and 43 percent said they would be unhappy if still doing 
the same job in five years the study called the copy desk the 
mount everest of newsroom discontent 
members of racial minorities are more pleased with their 
careers than white 85 percent of the minorities would choose 
newspapering again but 49 percent of the blacks aged 26 to 35 
think race is the biggest obstacle to their advancement 
nearly twothirds of those surveyed describe themselves as 
democrats or liberal or leaning that way twentytwo percent call 
themselves republicans or conservative and 17 percent define 
themselves as independent 
a lack of feedback is more important to most participants than 
pay thirtysix percent said they would improve communication if 
they were put in charge while only 25 percent would improve pay and 
benefits three quarters said they got little or only occasional 
feedback on small papers pay was more important however than 
staff communication 
