<TEXT>
trade between china and the united states 
jumped by more than a third last year to a record 134 billion 
the us international trade commission reported monday 
the increase marked a rise from the 1987 total of 97 billion 
in 1978 the figure surpassed the 1 billion mark for the first 
time 
a high rate of industrial growth in china during 1988 was 
accompanied by record high inflation the report noted 
now like many other big us trading partners china sells much 
more than it buys in this country the us deficit with china rose 
to 34 billion from 28 billion the year before 
chinese sales to the united states rose by 22 billion to a 
total of more than 8 billion the increased chinese exports were 
largely manufactured goods such as toys and games but also items 
that take more technical skill to produce electrical sound 
recording and telecommunications equipment 
us exports were largely raw materials they also rose by 15 
billion to more than 5 billion with the increase led by 
chemicals wheat and softwood logs 
the report noted that a new agreement with china on limiting 
us imports of textiles went into effect last year there were 
also new accords on sea transport and on launching americanbuilt 
communications satellites from chinese soil an agreement on 
favorable us tariff rates was renewed 
us trade with the soviet union showed a surplus of 22 
billion twice the 1987 figure thanks to increased sales of corn 
wheat soybeans and fertilizers the soviets increased their 
exports by 155 million largely because of increased fuel oil 
shipments trade with the soviets was up but at 33 billion it 
was less than onefourth the china trade 
the report called attention to improvement in us trade 
relations with the soviets including lifting of the embargo on 
soviet furs extension of the agreemment on us grain sales 
increased interest among us companies in doing business in the 
soviet union 
overall us trade with communist countries reached a record 
192 billion in 1988 up from 138 billion the year before 
increases were registered with all eastern european countries with 
the exception of hungary 
