<TEXT>
a steady erosion of apartheid 
laws allows people of different races to use the same public 
restrooms libraries and elevators stand in the same line at the 
post offices eat at the same restaurants dance and drink together 
south african whites and blacks also can sit next to each other 
at theaters picnic at the same parks and in some instances share 
trains buses and beaches they worship together at some churches 
compete together on some soccer teams and running clubs they can 
have an interracial love affair or marriage without fear of arrest 
but in many other ways they remain divided by ignorance and 
fear that has developed over decades of forced separation 
the average south african wouldnt know how to mix across 
different groups he wouldnt know what to say after he said 
hello said bernard chalmers a white management consultant who 
conducts crosscultural encounter groups for businesses schools 
and churches 
the phenomenon has been described as an invisible berlin wall 
that keeps blacks and whites from understanding and communicating 
with each other even though many of them now interact in ways that 
once were prohibited 
such encounters have become a fad as more people are working and 
living next to someone whose culture they dont understand 
blacks find out whites are not really as rich as they think 
and whites find out things like the black guy loves his children 
said chalmers its really at that level of finding the other 
human being is there 
the rev nico smith a white minister who was shunned by family 
and friends when he moved into the black township of mamelodi 
outside pretoria belongs to a nationwide religious organization 
that brings blacks and whites together for meals home visits and 
church services 
apartheid has been very successful smith said white 
people tell me we discovered black people are ordinary people 
like we are just that one expression is an indication of the 
total alienation that developed over the years 
the chasm is so wide that black professionals often say they 
feel insulted and patronized usually by wellmeaning white 
colleagues who think they are reaching across the cultural divide 
more dangerous than apartheid are the pseudoliberals who are 
really saying if you do things like me and come to be like me and 
take on my culture i will accept you said gabriel setiloane a 
black professor of religion at the mostly white university of cape 
town all my life i have been among these people who are 
insulting me every day because they can only accept me when i speak 
their language and do things they want to be done 
i tell them at the university how much of the african 
understanding of the being of life of values are coming into your 
curriculum your articles your relationships otherwise it means 
you have black students at the university that you are making 
white 
pearl ntuli a black marketing manager for a black magazine 
africa now said i do make friends with white people especially 
now that people are trying hard to reach out but some people end 
up being too patronizing we blacks are also very suspicious of 
them we think they they dont really mean it but eventually you 
learn to recognize the good people 
more businesses are recognizing they must rely on the growing 
black labor force to fill supervisory professional and technical 
positions and that the black majority population is their primary 
market 
daniel pholo the black manager of social programs for makro 
wholesale stores said his company has a program to promote black 
managers and a multiracial employee soccer team he instructs white 
supervisors about black employees different needs such as more 
time for lengthy mourning rituals after the death of a loved one 
but black and white makro employees seldom visit each other on 
weekends he said because few blacks have transport to white 
suburbs and whites are scared to go into black townships 
the government has moved from a policy of forcing apartheid on 
everyone to proposing the creation of integated residential areas 
for those who prefer them however it is committed to maintaining 
separate voter rolls and providing segregated neighborhoods public 
schools and hospitals for whites who want them 
apartheid laws still deny the black majority of 28 million the 
right to vote on national affairs assign them to underfunded 
schools with unqualified teachers and force most of them to live 
in impoverished rural homelands or underdeveloped overcrowded 
urban townships blacks are tried by white judges for breaking laws 
passed by white legislators all municipal governments have power 
to prohibit blacks from using any public facility 
blacks and whites get to know each other most easily as 
nextdoor neighbors said john kaneberman head of the independent 
south african institute of race relations he said an estimated 
100000 to 200000 black people live illegally in white 
neighborhoods engaged in grassroots civil disobedience on a mass 
scale 
the government seldom enforces the residential segregation law 
in most of the mixed areas kaneberman said whites are either 
apathetic or enthusiastic about their black indian or mixedrace 
neighbors 
there have been a couple of ugly incidents he added but 
because the opposition has in fact been pretty small the 
government has been able to turn a blind eye to it 
social contact across the color line is the rule now rather 
than the exception kaneberman said in the process of 
economic integration people are just discovering that when you 
actually meet people of another race they are not as terrible as 
you were brainwashed into believing 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

