<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday agreed to decide 
whether florida may block an illinoisbased bank holding company 
from establishing an industrial savings bank in miami 
the justices said they will review the dispute even though bush 
administration lawyers asked for their views said a change in 
federal banking law may have made the case moot 
continental bank corporation based in illinois filed an 
application with the florida department of banking an finance in 
1981 to establish and run an industrial savings bank in miami 
the proposed bank would not accept demand deposits or make 
commercial loans making it a socalled nonbank bank that 
fell outside the federal laws definition of banks 
but deposits in the proposed bank would be insured by the 
federal deposit insurance corporation 
the application was denied and continental subsequently sued in 
federal court the suit alleged that floridas denial of the 
application was unconstitutional 
under federal banking law a bank holding company based in one 
state may not establish a bank in another state unless the latter 
states laws specifically authorize it to do so 
but because nonbank banks fall outside the scope of federal 
banking law state regulation of such institutions is subject to 
the constitutions requirement that states not unduly interfere 
with or discriminate against interstate commerce 
while the continental case was pending before a federal appeals 
court in 1987 federal banking law was amended to include in the 
definition of bank any institution the deposits of which are 
insured by the fdic 
because the proposed industrial savings bank in miami was to be 
fdicinsured it fell within the scope of federal banking law and 
subject to floridas legally authorized discrimination 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals however refused to 
declare the case moot 
it instead ruled that the florida law banning the industrial 
savings bank was unconstitutional the appeals court said it could 
say that the change in federal law would make continentals 
operation of the florida institution banking activity in 
every instance 
gerald a lewis who heads the state department of banking and 
finance then sought supreme court review 
the case is lewis vs continental bank corp 871955 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

