<TEXT>
champion insurance co the 
fourthlargest auto insurer in louisiana was declared insolvent 
monday and was placed under control of louisiana insurance 
commissioner doug green 
officials said policyholders will remain covered by the 
louisiana guaranty association a group of insurance firms that 
handles unpaid claims by any company that fails 
district judge joseph keogh signed the order placing the company 
under state control at about the same time employees left work at 
champions baton rouge headquarters saying they had been told the 
company was closing and that they were not to return 
keoghs order declared champion insolvent and said the insurance 
commission is to liquidate the company 
keogh acted shortly after green took the matter to court green 
was under pressure from the governor and attorney general to 
investigate the company which has been linked to him in ethics 
investigations 
in his petition green said champion may not have the money to 
pay claims in louisiana for months the insurance commissioner has 
said champion was financially sound 
the company which recently gave up its license to operate in 
alabama sold slightly less than 1 million a week in premiums in 
louisiana officials said in the two states the company had 
324000 customers mostly in highrisk policies champion also 
writes policies in tennessee 
louisiana has at least 1300 complaints on file from champion 
policyholders who said they had trouble getting claims paid more 
than 7000 suits have been filed against the company in the state 
greens office said champion has refused to pay or has delayed 
payment of fees for attorneys hired by the company to defend suits 
involving policyholders 
green has been under fire from gov buddy roemer and attorney 
general william guste who have accused him of being too closely 
tied with the owners of champion a lawsuit alleges that a 
championrelated company illegally bankrolled greens campaign 
green could not be reached immediately for comment 
the insurance department in alabama filed a complaint against 
the company in march seeking to revoke its license to do business 
that state claimed champion was in unsound financial condition 
champion subsequently gave up its license to do business in alabama 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

